/*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*\
  Minimise the total module cost (sum of Guthrie totalModuleCost across
  every costed unit) for a small reactor -> heater -> separator process,
  by tuning two design variables:

      * reactor.V_R       reactor volume       [0.002, 0.010]  m^3
      * heater.Q          heater duty          [   0,    500]  W
                          (credo-pure: hardware, not outlet T)

  Pedagogical note: this case uses only CAPEX (purchased + bare-module
  + total-module cost via Guthrie correlations).  The optimum is NOT the
  lower corner one might naively expect.  Nelder-Mead (8 moves) lands at:

      reactor.V_R = 0.008070 m^3   (INTERIOR, not on a bound)
      heater.Q    = 500 W          (driven hard to its UPPER bound)
      objective   = 9.346728e+05 EUR

  Why higher duty is cheaper here: the dominant cost is the heat exchanger
  (~916 k of ~935 k total), whose area A = Q/(U*LMTD) = Q/6000 gives only
  ~0.083 m^2 at Q = 500 W -- two orders of magnitude BELOW the Turton
  correlation's valid range (A in [10, 1000] m^2).  In that extrapolated
  tail the quadratic K3*(log10 A)^2 term makes a SMALLER area MORE
  expensive, so the simplex pushes Q up to grow A and slide down the cost
  curve.  This optimum is therefore partly an artifact of extrapolating the
  HX correlation below Smin -- a deliberate teaching point: cost models bite
  outside their validity range.  The exercise verifies:

      1. the OptimizationDriver wires correctly to the post-processing
         chain (sizing + costing) so that result.costs is populated
         before extracting the objective;
      2. the Nelder-Mead simplex contracts cleanly and parks one variable
         on an active box-constraint (Q at its upper bound) while the other
         lands in the interior -- a mixed optimum, not a degenerate corner;
      3. the student reads the validity range off a cost correlation and
         sees why OPEX terms (utility + raw-material) are needed for a
         physically meaningful trade-off -- motivating a CostingModel OPEX
         extension.

  The case converges in 8 simplex moves with simplexInit 0.15.
\*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/

type    optimization;
method  nelderMead;

variables
(
    {
        path     units[0].operation.V_R;
        min      0.002;
        max      0.010;
        initial  0.005;
    }
    {
        path     units[1].operation.Q;
        min        0.0;
        max      500.0;
        initial  150.0;
    }
);

objective
{
    kind     costTotal;
    path     totalModuleCost;
    sense    minimise;
}

options
{
    maxIter     80;
    tolX        1e-4;
    tolF        1e-4;
    simplexInit 0.15;
}

report
{
    file        optimization_history.csv;
}
